      "criterion": "Arithmetic operators are used correctly to calculate restocking fees as percentages of base price and to compute final adjusted prices (e.g., adjusted price = base price + base price * fee rate).",
      "related_learning_objective": 3
    },
    {
      "criterion": "Relational operators are used to compare stock quantities against restocking thresholds and zero to determine which pricing rule applies (e.g., stock <= threshold, stock > 0).",
      "related_learning_objective": 4
    },
    {
      "criterion": "Logical operators are used to combine multiple validation conditions in boolean expressions (e.g., stock >= 0 && price > 0 && !string.IsNullOrEmpty(itemName)).",
      "related_learning_objective": 5
    },
    {
      "criterion": "Conditional statements (if/else if/else) correctly implement the three-tier pricing logic: no adjustment for sufficient stock, 15% fee for low stock, and 25% fee for zero stock.",
      "related_learning_objective": 7
    },
    {
      "criterion": "A loop (for, while, or foreach) is implemented to iterate through multiple catalog items and process each one by calling the price adjustment method.",
      "related_learning_objective": 9
    },
    {
      "criterion": "At least one method with parameters (item name, stock, price, threshold) and a return type (adjusted price) is defined and called correctly within the processing loop.",
      "related_learning_objective": 10
    },
    {
      "criterion": "Exception handling using try/catch blocks is implemented to catch and handle invalid catalog data exceptions during processing, allowing the program to continue with remaining items.",
      "related_learning_objective": 13
    },
    {
      "criterion": "A custom exception type is defined for invalid catalog data and is thrown when validation fails (negative stock, non-positive price, or empty item name).",
      "related_learning_objective": 14
    },
    {
      "criterion": "Items with stock above the restocking threshold return the original base price with no adjustment applied.",
      "related_learning_objective": 7
    },
    {
      "criterion": "Items with stock at or below the restocking threshold but greater than zero have exactly 15% added to the base price.",
      "related_learning_objective": 3
    },
    {
      "criterion": "Items with exactly zero stock have exactly 25% added to the base price.",
      "related_learning_objective": 4
    }
  ],
  "hints": [
    "Begin by identifying the data elements you need for each catalog item: name, stock level, price, and a threshold value. Choose appropriate types for each.",
    "Think about what makes catalog data 'invalid'. What conditions would make an item unprocessable?",
    "The pricing logic has three distinct cases based on stock levels. Use relational operators to compare stock against thresholds and zero.",
    "Consider creating a method that takes item details as parameters and returns the adjusted price. This makes your logic reusable.",
    "When validating inputs, you may need to check multiple conditions at once. Logical operators can help combine these checks into a single boolean expression.",
    "To process multiple items, you'll need a loop structure. Think about how to store the item data and iterate through it.",
    "Restocking fees are percentages. Remember that 15% means multiplying by 0.15, and you'll need to add this to the original price, not replace it.",
    "Create a custom exception class to represent invalid catalog data. This exception should be thrown when validation fails.",
    "Use try/catch blocks around the processing logic for each item. If one item fails, the program should handle the error and continue with the next item.",
    "Test with boundary values: stock exactly at threshold, stock at zero, and stock just above/below threshold values."
  ]
}


