{
  "task_name": "Request Trace & Rate Guard: Map a Custom Middleware Branch for Checkout Attempts",
  "skill_category": "ASP.NET Core Logic",
  "scenario": {
    "story": "The platform team noticed repeated automated checkout attempts that create noisy logs and occasionally cause timeouts. They want a lightweight guard on checkout-related endpoints that (1) assigns a trace id to every request for correlation, (2) rate-limits repeated attempts from the same client within a short window, and (3) clearly demonstrates how branching the request pipeline works for a specific route prefix. This must be implemented without adding a full security system—just a focused pipeline feature.",
    "requirement": "Implement ONE feature: a custom middleware-based guard that runs only for requests under a checkout route prefix (e.g., /checkout). Use Map (or equivalent branching) to isolate the pipeline for that prefix. Inside the branch, add middleware that reads/modifies HttpContext (request headers and connection info), sets response headers/status codes, and uses Run for early termination when rate limits are exceeded. Log decisions (allowed vs blocked) and attach a trace id to responses so downstream services can correlate requests."
  },
  "targeted_objectives": [11, 12, 16],
  "additional_skills_required": [
    {
      "skill_name": "C# Basics",
      "used_learning_goal": 9,
      "justification": "A small in-memory rate limit store requires iterating over recent timestamps per client (e.g., foreach) to prune old entries and count attempts deterministically."
    },
    {
      "skill_name": "OOP (Object-Oriented Programming)",
      "used_learning_goal": 7,
      "justification": "Defining a focused abstraction (interface) for a rate-limit store enables clean middleware design and makes automated evaluation easier by allowing a fake store in tests."
    }
  ],
  "instructions": [
    "In Program.cs, create a dedicated pipeline branch for checkout endpoints using Map (or an equivalent branch mechanism). The branch must only apply to a specific path prefix so that non-checkout endpoints are unaffected.",
    "Implement a custom middleware that runs within that checkout branch. The middleware should generate or reuse a request trace identifier and attach it to the current request context so subsequent components can read it.",
    "Use HttpContext to access request data needed for rate limiting (for example, a client identifier from a request header or the remote IP address). Decide on one stable identifier and document it in code comments.",
    "Implement an in-memory rate-limiting store (small, non-persistent) that tracks recent checkout attempts per client for a short rolling window. Keep it deterministic and simple—this is a guardrail, not a full security solution.",
    "In the middleware, check the number of attempts for the current client within the window. If the limit is exceeded, terminate the request early using the pipeline (e.g., by setting an appropriate status code like 429 and writing a small response body).",
    "Ensure the pipeline branch demonstrates Use and Run meaningfully: Use for normal pass-through behavior; Run (or an equivalent terminal delegate) for blocked requests so the controller/action is never reached.",
    "Add logging inside the middleware to record when requests are allowed vs blocked, including the trace id and the chosen client identifier.",
    "Demonstrate understanding of execution order: confirm (by code structure) that the trace id is assigned before any rate-limit decision is logged and before any terminal response is produced.",
    "Keep the implementation medium-sized: one middleware class, one small store abstraction + implementation, and Program.cs wiring, totaling roughly 40–150 lines of C#."
  ],
  "validation_criteria": [
    {
      "criterion": "A custom middleware class is implemented and invoked as part of the ASP.NET Core request pipeline for checkout-prefixed requests.",
      "related_learning_objective": 11
    },
    {
      "criterion": "The request pipeline uses Map (or equivalent branching) to apply the checkout guard only to a specific path prefix, and requests outside that prefix are not affected by the guard logic.",
      "related_learning_objective": 12
    },
    {
      "criterion": "Within the checkout branch, the pipeline demonstrates Use for pass-through behavior and Run (or an equivalent terminal delegate) for early termination when rate limiting triggers.",
      "related_learning_objective": 12
    },
    {
      "criterion": "The code structure reflects correct execution order: the trace id is generated/assigned before logging the allow/block decision and before any terminal response is produced.",
      "related_learning_objective": 16
    },
    {
      "criterion": "The code structure reflects correct execution order: when rate limiting triggers, downstream components (e.g., MVC endpoints) are not executed because the branch terminates the request.",
      "related_learning_objective": 16
    },
    {
      "criterion": "The in-memory rate-limit store prunes or ignores attempts outside the rolling time window so older attempts do not count toward the current limit.",
      "related_learning_objective": 0
    },
    {
      "criterion": "When the rate limit is exceeded, the response status code is set to 429 and the response includes a trace id value (e.g., in a header or body) to support correlation.",
      "related_learning_objective": 0
    },
    {
      "criterion": "When the rate limit is not exceeded, the request is allowed to proceed through the checkout branch without being terminated by the guard logic.",
      "related_learning_objective": 0
    }
  ],
  "hints": [
    "Start by branching the pipeline by path prefix; verify in your head which requests should enter the branch and which should not.",
    "Decide how clients will be identified for rate limiting (header-based client id is easiest to test; IP-based is also possible).",
    "A rolling-window limiter can be implemented by storing timestamps per client and removing old timestamps before counting.",
    "Use terminal branching (Run) only when blocking; otherwise call the next delegate so the request can continue.",
    "To demonstrate execution order, ensure trace assignment happens at the top of the middleware and that all log statements include the trace id."
  ]
}

