{
  "task_name": "Extensible Promotion Pricing Engine for Invoice Checkout",
  "skill_category": "Design Patterns & SOLID",
  "scenario": {
    "story": "A SaaS company sells monthly add-ons (e.g., extra seats, storage packs). During checkout, the invoice total must reflect active promotions such as “10% off for annual prepay customers” or “$20 off when subtotal exceeds $200”. Marketing adds new promotion types frequently, and Finance requires deterministic, testable totals.",
    "requirement": "Implement a small promotion-pricing feature that computes an invoice total from line items and applies a configurable set of promotions. The design must allow adding new promotion types without changing the pricing engine. Promotions must be created from simple configuration records (e.g., type + parameters) without exposing instantiation logic. The pricing engine must load promotions from an abstraction (repository) and depend only on abstractions."
  },
  "targeted_objectives": [2, 5, 6, 8, 9],
  "additional_skills_required": [
    {
      "skill_name": "OOP (Object-Oriented Programming)",
      "used_learning_goal": 7,
      "justification": "Required to define and implement interfaces for promotions, repositories, and factories in a strongly-typed way."
    }
  ],
  "instructions": [
    "Define a small model for checkout input (e.g., a line item with unit price and quantity) and an output result that includes subtotal, total discount, and final total.",
    "Create a promotion abstraction representing a single discount algorithm that can be applied to a subtotal (and optionally inspect line items). Ensure each promotion implementation encapsulates one discount rule.",
    "Implement a pricing engine class that accepts a collection of promotions and applies them in order to produce the final total. The pricing engine must not contain conditional logic for specific promotion types; it should rely on polymorphism (strategy).",
    "Introduce a promotion repository abstraction that returns the enabled promotion configurations for a given customer segment or checkout context. Provide a simple in-memory implementation to support testing and automated evaluation.",
    "Implement a factory that converts a promotion configuration record (e.g., { type, parameters }) into a concrete promotion instance. The pricing engine should obtain promotion instances via this factory (directly or indirectly), not by using 'new' for each promotion type.",
    "Ensure the design is extendable: adding a new promotion type should require adding a new class (and minimal registration/wiring) but not editing the pricing engine’s core calculation logic.",
    "Add basic guardrails in code (e.g., non-negative totals, promotions cannot increase price) so the behavior is deterministic and easy to test."
  ],
  "validation_criteria": [
    {
      "criterion": "Pricing engine does not use a switch/if chain on promotion \"type\" to apply discounts; discount application is performed via polymorphism through the promotion abstraction.",
      "related_learning_objective": 9
    },
    {
      "criterion": "At least two distinct promotion strategies exist (e.g., percentage-off and fixed-amount-off) and both can be applied by the same pricing engine without modifying the pricing engine code.",
      "related_learning_objective": 2
    },
    {
      "criterion": "Pricing engine depends on abstractions for obtaining promotions (e.g., repository and/or factory interfaces) and does not directly instantiate repository or promotion implementations.",
      "related_learning_objective": 5
    },
    {
      "criterion": "A repository abstraction exists to retrieve enabled promotion configurations, and the implementation can be swapped (e.g., in-memory repository used in tests) without changing pricing engine logic.",
      "related_learning_objective": 6
    },
    {
      "criterion": "A factory abstraction exists that creates concrete promotion instances from configuration records without exposing instantiation logic to the pricing engine.",
      "related_learning_objective": 8
    },
    {
      "criterion": "Given line items totaling 250.00 and promotions: fixed 20.00 off (min subtotal 200.00) then 10% off, the final total equals 207.00 (subtotal 250.00, discounts 20.00 + 23.00).",
      "related_learning_objective": 0
    },
    {
      "criterion": "If a fixed-amount promotion discount exceeds the current amount, the applied discount is capped so the running total never becomes negative.",
      "related_learning_objective": 0
    }
  ],
  "hints": [
    "Start by writing a pure calculation method that computes subtotal from line items; keep it independent from promotions.",
    "Introduce an interface for a discount rule that can compute a discount based on current subtotal and inputs; the pricing engine should only call this interface.",
    "If you feel tempted to write 'if (type == ...)' inside the engine, move that logic into separate promotion classes and let the engine operate on a list of them.",
    "Model promotion configuration as simple data (type + numeric parameters). Let a factory translate configuration into a concrete promotion object.",
    "Use an in-memory repository that returns a list of promotion configurations so tests can control which promotions are enabled.",
    "Verify the ordering effect by applying two promotions sequentially and ensuring the second promotion runs on the reduced total (or whichever rule you decide—make it consistent and testable)."
  ]
}

{
  "task_name": "Notification Scheduling for Task Reminders with Extensible Channels",
  "skill_category": "Design Patterns & SOLID",
  "scenario": {
    "story": "A productivity app lets users create tasks with optional reminders. When a reminder time is reached, the system must send a notification. Initially the business only supports email reminders, but it will soon add SMS and push notifications. The team wants the reminder scheduling logic to remain stable while new delivery channels are introduced.",
    "requirement": "Implement a reminder notification feature that selects the correct notification channel (email/sms/push) at runtime based on a task’s reminder settings and user preferences, then sends the message. Reminders must be fetched through a repository abstraction. Notification senders must be created via a factory so that channel instantiation logic is not exposed to the scheduling service. The scheduling service must depend only on abstractions and be extendable to new channels without modification."
  },
  "targeted_objectives": [1, 2, 5, 8, 9],
  "additional_skills_required": [],
  "instructions": [
    "Define a minimal data model representing a task reminder to be processed (e.g., task id, title, reminder time, user id, preferred channel, and a processed flag). Keep models small and focused.",
    "Create a repository abstraction responsible only for reminder persistence queries needed by this feature (e.g., fetch due reminders, mark reminder as processed). Provide a simple in-memory implementation for evaluation.",
    "Define a notification strategy abstraction (a small interface) that can send a reminder message given the reminder data.",
    "Implement at least two concrete notification strategies (e.g., Email and SMS) with predictable behavior suitable for tests (e.g., returning a result object rather than actually sending).",
    "Implement a factory that takes a channel identifier (and any needed configuration) and returns the correct notification strategy instance. The scheduling logic must not instantiate strategies directly.",
    "Implement a reminder scheduler/service class with a single responsibility: retrieve due reminders, select the correct channel strategy, send notifications, and mark reminders as processed when sending succeeds.",
    "Design for extensibility: adding a new channel should require adding a new strategy class and updating factory wiring/registration, without changing the scheduler’s core flow.",
    "Add guardrails: do not send reminders with no reminder time, do not re-send already processed reminders, and handle unknown channels deterministically (e.g., return failure result without marking processed)."
  ],
  "validation_criteria": [
    {
      "criterion": "Reminder scheduler/service class only orchestrates fetching due reminders, sending via a notification abstraction, and marking processed; it does not contain persistence logic beyond calling repository methods.",
      "related_learning_objective": 1
    },
    {
      "criterion": "Adding a new notification channel strategy does not require modifying the scheduler/service logic (no channel-specific if/switch inside the scheduler).",
      "related_learning_objective": 2
    },
    {
      "criterion": "Scheduler/service depends on abstractions (e.g., repository interface, factory interface, notification strategy interface) and not on concrete implementations.",
      "related_learning_objective": 5
    },
    {
      "criterion": "A factory is used to obtain the notification strategy based on the channel identifier; the scheduler does not instantiate concrete strategies with 'new'.",
      "related_learning_objective": 8
    },
    {
      "criterion": "At runtime, different notification strategies can be selected interchangeably based on reminder channel, and the scheduler uses the same call path to send through each strategy.",
      "related_learning_objective": 9
    },
    {
      "criterion": "Repository abstraction provides a method to retrieve only reminders due at or before a given 'now' timestamp and that are not already processed.",
      "related_learning_objective": 0
    },
    {
      "criterion": "When a due reminder is sent successfully, the reminder is marked processed via the repository exactly once.",
      "related_learning_objective": 0
    },
    {
      "criterion": "If the reminder channel is unknown (factory cannot create a strategy), the reminder is not marked processed.",
      "related_learning_objective": 0
    },
    {
      "criterion": "Reminders with null/absent reminder time are never returned as due reminders and are never sent.",
      "related_learning_objective": 0
    }
  ],
  "hints": [
    "Start by defining what data a reminder needs to send a message and what the scheduler needs to decide whether it is due.",
    "Keep your repository interface small: only the queries/commands required by this feature should exist there.",
    "Use one interface for “send reminder” and have each channel implement it; the scheduler should only know that interface.",
    "If you find yourself writing channel selection logic in the scheduler, move it into a factory that returns the correct strategy.",
    "Make sending testable by returning a simple result (success/failure + reason) instead of performing real I/O.",
    "Decide a clear rule for unknown channels and ensure your code follows it consistently (especially for marking processed)."
  ]
}

