{
  "task_name": "Implement a Coupon-Based Basket Discount Engine with Polymorphic Rules",
  "skill_category": "OOP (Object-Oriented Programming)",
  "scenario": {
    "story": "A small online shop is adding promo codes to its checkout. A basket can contain multiple items, and customers can enter a coupon code (e.g., percentage off, fixed amount off, or buy-X-get-Y). The business wants a single discount engine that can evaluate a coupon against the basket, apply the correct discount, and return a clear breakdown for the checkout screen.",
    "requirement": "Implement a small, standalone discount engine (no database, no web layer) that models a shopping basket and applies exactly one coupon-based discount rule. Use an abstract base class for discount rules with derived rule types that override the discount calculation. The basket should use composition to contain basket items and should expose methods to add items and calculate totals. Include at least one interface to standardize how the checkout process asks for a discount result."
  },
  "targeted_objectives": [6, 7, 8],
  "additional_skills_required": [
    {
      "skill_name": "C# Basics",
      "used_learning_goal": 7,
      "justification": "Conditional logic is required to validate coupon applicability (e.g., minimum subtotal, matching SKU, quantity thresholds) and to select whether a discount should be applied."
    }
  ],
  "instructions": [
    "Create a small set of classes representing a basket and its items. The basket must hold item objects (composition) and expose methods to add items and compute the subtotal.",
    "Define an interface that represents a component capable of producing a discount result for a basket given a coupon code. The rest of the code should depend on this interface, not a concrete rule type.",
    "Design an abstract base class for a coupon rule that contains shared data (e.g., coupon code, a human-readable description) and a method that calculates the discount amount for a given basket. Make the shared data readable from outside but not freely mutable.",
    "Implement at least two concrete coupon rule types derived from the abstract base class (for example: percentage-off with a minimum subtotal, and fixed-amount-off capped by subtotal). Each derived class must override the calculation method to implement its own business rule.",
    "Implement a small engine class that implements the interface and uses polymorphism: it should hold a collection of coupon rules, find the matching rule by coupon code, and execute the overridden calculation method to produce the discount.",
    "Return a discount result object that includes: applied coupon code (or null/empty if none), discount amount, and final total after discount. Ensure totals never go below zero.",
    "Keep the solution focused: implement only this feature (basket + coupon discount evaluation). Avoid adding persistence, DI containers, controllers, or extra layers."
  ],
  "validation_criteria": [
    {
      "criterion": "At least one derived coupon rule class overrides a virtual/abstract calculation method from the base coupon rule class, and the engine calls the method through a base-class reference to achieve polymorphic behavior.",
      "related_learning_objective": 6
    },
    {
      "criterion": "An interface is defined for producing a discount result from a basket and coupon code, and the discount engine class implements that interface.",
      "related_learning_objective": 7
    },
    {
      "criterion": "An abstract base class exists for coupon rules and it cannot be instantiated directly; concrete coupon rules inherit from it.",
      "related_learning_objective": 8
    },
    {
      "criterion": "If the coupon code does not match any known rule, the returned discount amount is 0 and the final total equals the basket subtotal.",
