  "skill_category": "OOP (Object-Oriented Programming)",
  "scenario": {
    "story": "A B2C/B2B store sells the same products to different customer types. Retail customers pay list price, business customers get contracted discounts, and VIP customers get a different discount policy. The checkout team wants one pricing component that can price a basket line-by-line based on the customer type and eligibility rules, while keeping customer details encapsulated.",
    "requirement": "Implement a standalone pricing feature that calculates the final total for a basket given a customer. Model customers using inheritance (a base customer class with derived customer types). Use an interface to represent discount-eligibility behavior. Encapsulate sensitive customer data (e.g., internal flags or contract discount rate) using access modifiers. The pricing service must treat customers polymorphically and compute totals using a LINQ projection."
  },
  "targeted_objectives": [5, 7, 4],
  "additional_skills_required": [
    {
      "skill_name": "LINQ & Advanced C# Concepts",
      "used_learning_goal": 1,
      "justification": "Required to project basket lines into per-line priced totals (e.g., Select line -> lineTotal) before summing to a final total."
    },
    {
      "skill_name": "C# Basics",
      "used_learning_goal": 7,
      "justification": "Required for branching logic such as applying different discount rules based on customer type and eligibility thresholds."
    },
    {
      "skill_name": "C# Basics",
      "used_learning_goal": 10,
      "justification": "Required to define methods with parameters/return types for pricing operations (e.g., calculating line totals and final totals)."
    }
  ],
  "instructions": [
    "Model a basket with line items (composition). Each line item should contain at minimum: product identifier (or name), unit price, and quantity.",
    "Create a base customer class that represents shared customer data. Keep any sensitive or rule-driving fields non-public and expose only what checkout needs via safe properties or methods.",
    "Create at least two derived customer classes that represent different pricing behavior (e.g., business vs VIP). Use inheritance to share common customer state while allowing specialized behavior.",
    "Define an interface that represents whether a customer is eligible for a discount (or provides a discount factor). At least one customer type should implement this interface and another customer type should not (to make the interface meaningful).",
    "Implement a pricing service class with a method that takes a basket and a base-customer reference and returns a pricing summary (e.g., subtotal, discount amount, final total). The pricing service must not rely on concrete customer types in its public API.",
    "Within pricing calculations, use LINQ to transform basket lines into line totals and compute the subtotal/final total from those projections.",
    "Apply business rules such as: no discounts for retail customers; business customers get a percentage discount if they are eligible; VIP customers have a different rule (for example, a higher discount but capped per order). Keep these rules testable and deterministic.",
    "Ensure discount never makes the final total negative, and handle invalid basket input (e.g., negative price or non-positive quantity) consistently (exception or failure result)."
  ],
  "validation_criteria": [
    {
      "criterion": "A customer type is implemented as a derived class inheriting from a base customer class, demonstrating inheritance for customer modeling.",
