      "criterion": "An interface representing discount eligibility (or discount provision) is defined, and at least one customer type implements it.",
      "related_learning_objective": 7
    },
    {
      "criterion": "Sensitive customer state used in discount decisions (e.g., contract rate, VIP flag, eligibility state) is encapsulated using non-public access modifiers and cannot be modified directly from outside the customer class.",
      "related_learning_objective": 4
    },
    {
      "criterion": "The pricing service accepts the base customer type (not a derived type) and correctly prices baskets for at least two different customer derived instances passed via the same method signature.",
      "related_learning_objective": 0
    },
    {
      "criterion": "The pricing service uses LINQ Select to project basket lines into per-line totals (unit price * quantity) as part of computing the subtotal.",
      "related_learning_objective": 0
    },
    {
      "criterion": "For a retail customer (non-eligible), the discount amount is 0 and final total equals subtotal.",
      "related_learning_objective": 0
    },
    {
      "criterion": "For an eligible business customer, the discount amount equals subtotal * businessDiscountRate and final total equals subtotal minus discount.",
      "related_learning_objective": 0
    },
    {
      "criterion": "For a VIP customer, the VIP discount rule differs from the business rule (e.g., different percentage and/or a cap), and the computed final total reflects that distinct rule.",
      "related_learning_objective": 0
    },
    {
      "criterion": "If any line item has a negative unit price or non-positive quantity, the implementation follows the chosen invalid-input policy (exception thrown or failure result) and does not return a successful pricing summary.",
      "related_learning_objective": 0
    }
  ],
  "hints": [
    "Begin by implementing basket line total calculation (unit price * quantity) and subtotal aggregation.",
    "Add the base customer class first, then create derived customer types with only the extra fields needed for pricing decisions.",
    "Introduce the discount-eligibility interface so the pricing service can detect discount capability without checking concrete types everywhere.",
    "Use encapsulation to prevent external code from setting discount rates arbitrarily; expose them through controlled properties or methods.",
    "Add LINQ projection for line totals, then layer discount rules on top and verify totals remain non-negative."
  ]
