{
  "task_name": "Invoice Total Calculator with Tiered Discounts and Payment Fee Rules",
  "skill_category": "C# Basics",
  "scenario": {
    "story": "A small B2B supplier is replacing a spreadsheet-based invoicing process with a simple C# module that calculates invoice totals. Each invoice contains multiple line items and can optionally include a promotional discount code. The accounting team also charges different payment processing fees depending on the payment method selected.",
    "requirement": "Implement a standalone C# feature that calculates an invoice summary (subtotal, discount amount, payment fee, and final total) from a list of line items. The calculation must apply tiered discounts based on subtotal and an additional discount based on a promo code, then add a payment fee determined by payment method. The module must validate input quantities/prices and throw a custom exception for invalid invoice data."
  },
  "targeted_objectives": [7, 8, 9, 10, 14],
  "additional_skills_required": [
    {
      "skill_name": "OOP (Object-Oriented Programming)",
      "used_learning_goal": 1,
      "justification": "A small, testable feature needs at least two classes (e.g., line item model + calculator/service) with properties and methods to keep the logic organized while staying within the 40–150 line scope."
    }
  ],
  "instructions": [
    "Create a minimal set of types to represent invoice input and the computed output (e.g., a line item type with description, unit price, and quantity; and a result type with subtotal, discount, fee, and total). Keep it lightweight and focused on this single feature.",
    "Implement a calculator class that exposes one public method to compute the invoice summary from: (1) a collection of line items, (2) an optional promo code string, and (3) a payment method indicator.",
    "Inside the calculation method, iterate over all line items using a loop and compute the subtotal using arithmetic operators. Ensure each item's line total uses unitPrice * quantity and is added to the running subtotal.",
    "Validate inputs before and/or during the loop: quantities must be positive integers and unit prices must be non-negative. If validation fails, throw a custom exception type you define for invalid invoice data.",
    "Apply tiered discount rules using conditional statements (if/else if/else) based on the subtotal amount. Compute a discount amount (as a monetary value) rather than only computing a percentage.",
    "Apply an additional promo-code discount using conditional statements. The promo discount should depend on BOTH the promo code and a subtotal threshold, so the conditions require meaningful boolean logic (e.g., code matches AND subtotal exceeds a minimum).",
    "Determine the payment processing fee using a switch statement based on the payment method. At least three cases should exist (e.g., Card, BankTransfer, Cash), and the fee should be computed from the subtotal (or subtotal-after-discount) using arithmetic.",
    "Return the computed summary from the public method. Keep helper calculations in separate private methods with parameters and return types to keep the code readable and within a medium-sized scope.",
    "Make sure your custom exception is thrown (not just defined) and that its message contains enough information for automated tests to verify the reason (e.g., mentions whether quantity or price is invalid)."
