    },
    {
      "skill_name": "Design Patterns & SOLID",
      "used_learning_goal": 8,
      "justification": "A simple Factory pattern is required to choose and instantiate the correct sender based on the requested channel without exposing selection logic to callers."
    }
  ],
  "instructions": [
    "Define a notification request model with: ticketId (int), recipient (string), message (string), and preferredChannel (string). Keep it minimal.",
    "Define a notification result model with: usedChannel (string), fallbackUsed (bool), and infoMessage (string) that can be asserted by automated tests.",
    "Define an interface for a notification sender with one method that takes recipient and message and returns a boolean indicating whether sending was accepted/simulated as successful. Keep it synchronous for simplicity.",
    "Implement at least three sender classes that implement the interface (e.g., one for email, one for SMS, one for chat). Each sender should have at least one validation rule that can cause it to reject the send (for example: SMS rejects messages longer than a limit; chat rejects empty recipient; email rejects missing '@' in recipient).",
    "Create a factory class responsible for returning the correct sender implementation based on the preferredChannel. The factory should have a clear default behavior for unknown channels.",
    "Implement a service class with one public method that accepts the request and returns the result. This method should validate request basics (non-empty recipient/message, ticketId > 0) and throw a custom exception type you define if invalid.",
    "Use if/else logic combined with logical operators to decide when to fall back: if preferred channel is not supported OR the sender rejects the message, then try email as a fallback; if fallback also fails, return a result that indicates failure through infoMessage.",
    "Extract small helper methods with parameters and return types for repeated logic (e.g., ValidateRequest, IsValidEmailRecipient, BuildFallbackInfo) so the solution remains medium-sized and testable.",
    "Ensure the result clearly indicates whether fallback occurred and which channel was used so tests can verify correct factory selection and fallback behavior."
  ],
  "validation_criteria": [
    {
      "criterion": "Uses logical operators (&&, ||, !) to decide when fallback should happen (e.g., unsupported channel OR rejected send triggers fallback), and toggling inputs changes fallbackUsed.",
      "related_learning_objective": 5
    },
    {
      "criterion": "Uses if/else branching to validate request fields and to control flow between preferred send attempt and fallback attempt.",
      "related_learning_objective": 7
    },
    {
      "criterion": "Defines at least two methods with parameters and return types (beyond trivial property getters/setters) and the public service method calls them during processing.",
      "related_learning_objective": 10
    },
    {
      "criterion": "Defines and throws a custom exception type when ticketId <= 0 or recipient/message is null/empty, and the exception prevents any sender from being used.",
      "related_learning_objective": 14
    },
    {
      "criterion": "Uses a factory to select a sender implementation based on preferredChannel and returns a default sender (or null handling) for unknown channels.",
      "related_learning_objective": 0
    },
    {
      "criterion": "Implements at least three sender classes that conform to a common interface and can be returned by the factory.",
      "related_learning_objective": 0
    },
    {
      "criterion": "When preferred sender rejects a message due to its channel-specific rule, the service attempts email as fallback and sets fallbackUsed to true in the result.",
      "related_learning_objective": 0
    }
  ],
  "hints": [
    "Start by defining what inputs you need and what outputs tests should be able to assert (used channel and fallback flag).",
    "Keep senders simple: each sender can 'simulate' sending by returning true/false based on a rule rather than using real network APIs.",
    "Build the factory next: it should only decide which sender to return based on the channel string.",
    "Implement validation before any factory selection so invalid requests fail fast with your custom exception.",
    "Fallback is easiest if you structure the code as: try preferred -> if rejected/unsupported then try email -> build result."
  ]
