{
  "task_name": "Add Request/Response Timing Middleware with Route-Specific Pipeline Branch and Logging",
  "skill_category": "ASP.NET Core Logic",
  "scenario": {
    "story": "An internal finance API is used by multiple client apps, and operations wants better visibility into slow requests. They need a lightweight timing feature that measures how long certain endpoints take and returns the measured duration to clients for troubleshooting. For security and performance reasons, this timing header must only be added for a specific set of routes (the finance quote endpoints), not globally for the whole application.",
    "requirement": "Implement ONE feature: add a timing middleware that measures request processing time for a specific route branch (e.g., paths starting with /api/quotes). The middleware must log the elapsed time and add a response header with the elapsed milliseconds. Configure the request pipeline using Map to apply the middleware only to that route branch. Ensure the middleware uses HttpContext to read the request path and to set response headers."
  },
  "targeted_objectives": [11, 12, 17],
  "additional_skills_required": [
    {
      "skill_name": "C# Basics",
      "used_learning_goal": 10,
      "justification": "The middleware needs small helper methods (start/stop timing, formatting, header application) to keep logic readable and testable within a medium-sized implementation."
    }
  ],
  "instructions": [
    "Create a custom middleware class that measures elapsed time for a request from before calling the next delegate until after it completes. Keep the code small and focused.",
    "Use dependency injection in the middleware to get an ILogger instance and log one line per request including: HTTP method, request path, status code, and elapsed milliseconds.",
    "Modify the response using HttpContext so that, when the response is about to be sent, a header (e.g., X-Elapsed-Ms) is added with the measured duration in milliseconds.",
    "In Program.cs, branch the pipeline using Map so this middleware runs only when the request path matches the quote routes (for example, starts with /api/quotes). Do not apply it globally to every endpoint.",
    "Add a simple attribute-routed controller with at least one action method under the mapped route branch so automated tests can call it and verify both logging and headers. The action should return an IActionResult and set a normal 200 response for the happy path.",
    "Ensure the middleware does not throw if headers are already sent; use a safe mechanism (e.g., response OnStarting) to add headers at the right time."
  ],
  "validation_criteria": [
    {
      "criterion": "A custom middleware class exists and calls the next request delegate to allow the pipeline to continue (i.e., it does not terminate the request for valid paths).",
      "related_learning_objective": 11
    },
    {
      "criterion": "Program.cs branches the pipeline using app.Map (or equivalent) so the timing middleware is applied only for the /api/quotes route branch.",
      "related_learning_objective": 12
    },
    {
      "criterion": "For requests in the mapped branch, the middleware adds a response header (e.g., X-Elapsed-Ms) containing a numeric millisecond value.",
      "related_learning_objective": 0
    },
    {
      "criterion": "For requests outside the mapped branch, the response does not contain the timing header added by the middleware.",
      "related_learning_objective": 12
    },
    {
      "criterion": "The middleware uses ILogger to log a message that includes the request path and the measured elapsed milliseconds.",
      "related_learning_objective": 17
    },
    {
      "criterion": "The middleware reads the request path and/or method from HttpContext.Request and reads the status code from HttpContext.Response when writing the log entry.",
      "related_learning_objective": 0
    }
  ],
  "hints": [
    "Middleware should measure time around the call to the next delegate; the duration should include downstream processing (controllers, filters, etc.).",
    "If you need to ensure a header is added even when an exception occurs, consider placing header logic in a finally block and/or using Response.OnStarting.",
    "Map creates a sub-pipeline; make sure your endpoint routes align with the branch prefix you choose.",
    "Keep the controller action simple so tests can focus on middleware behavior rather than business logic."
  ]
}

