{
  "task_name": "Add Tiered Loyalty Points API Using OOP Encapsulation (Not Interfaces) and Custom Eligibility Rules",
  "skill_category": "ASP.NET Core Logic",
  "scenario": {
    "story": "A retailer runs a loyalty program where customers earn points for purchases. The rules differ by membership tier (Standard vs Premium) and include caps and exclusions (e.g., gift cards do not earn points, and points are capped per transaction). The company wants the points logic to be protected from accidental changes by API developers, so rule parameters should not be publicly mutable from controllers.",
    "requirement": "Implement ONE feature: a loyalty points calculation endpoint that accepts a membership tier in the route and a JSON body of purchase line items. The controller must validate input, choose the correct tier rules, and return the computed points. The points rules must be implemented using OOP encapsulation (private/protected state) and composition (a calculator that contains a rules object) rather than only an interface-based service. Return 400 on invalid input and 200 with the points breakdown on success."
  },
  "targeted_objectives": [5, 6, 7],
  "additional_skills_required": [
    {
      "skill_name": "OOP (Object-Oriented Programming)",
      "used_learning_goal": 9,
      "justification": "The calculator should be built using composition: a points calculator class should contain a tier rules object so rules can be swapped without exposing rule internals to the controller."
    },
    {
      "skill_name": "OOP (Object-Oriented Programming)",
      "used_learning_goal": 4,
      "justification": "Encapsulation is required to keep rule constants (earn rate, caps, excluded categories) private/protected and prevent controllers from mutating them directly."
    }
  ],
  "instructions": [
    "Create a request DTO representing a purchase: currency and a list of line items (sku/category, unit price, quantity). Add data annotations for required fields and valid numeric ranges.",
    "Implement a controller with attribute routing where the membership tier is provided as a route parameter (e.g., /api/loyalty/{tier}/points). Bind the request body from JSON.",
    "Return BadRequest if ModelState is invalid (e.g., missing items, non-positive quantities).",
    "Create an OOP design using composition: define a small rules class (or record) that holds earn rate, per-transaction cap, and excluded categories; then create a calculator class that contains a rules instance and exposes a single method to compute points.",
    "Ensure encapsulation: rule fields should not be publicly settable. The controller should only choose which tier to use and call the calculator, not modify rates or caps.",
    "Implement at least two tiers with different rules (e.g., Premium earns more points and has a higher cap). Select the rules based on the route tier string; if the tier is unknown, return BadRequest (or NotFound) with a clear error message.",
    "In the response, return a breakdown that makes evaluation easy: subtotal eligible amount, excluded amount, raw points before cap, and final points after cap."
  ],
  "validation_criteria": [
    {
      "criterion": "The endpoint uses attribute routing with a {tier} route parameter and binds the JSON request body to a DTO.",
      "related_learning_objective": 5
    },
    {
      "criterion": "The controller action returns HTTP 400 (BadRequest) when ModelState is invalid due to data-annotation failures (e.g., quantity <= 0 or missing required fields).",
      "related_learning_objective": 7
    },
    {
      "criterion": "For a valid request and a supported tier, the action returns HTTP 200 (OK) with a response payload that includes final points as a non-negative integer.",
      "related_learning_objective": 6
    },
    {
      "criterion": "The points calculator is implemented using composition (a calculator class contains a rules object) rather than placing all rule constants directly in the controller.",
      "related_learning_objective": 0
    },
    {
      "criterion": "Rule parameters (earn rate, cap, excluded categories) are encapsulated (private/protected or read-only) and are not publicly settable from the controller.",
      "related_learning_objective": 0
    },
    {
      "criterion": "Items in an excluded category do not contribute to eligible subtotal or points, and this is reflected in the response breakdown.",
      "related_learning_objective": 0
    },
    {
      "criterion": "When computed points exceed the tier cap, the final points returned by the endpoint equal the cap value.",
      "related_learning_objective": 0
    }
  ],
  "hints": [
    "Keep the HTTP layer thin: validate input and select a tier, then delegate the computation to a calculator class.",
    "Composition works well here: rules are data, calculator is behavior. The controller should never directly change rule data.",
    "Include a breakdown in the response so tests can verify exclusions and caps without relying on hidden logic.",
    "Make tier selection deterministic (e.g., normalize to lowercase) so route handling is easy to test."
  ]
}

{
  "task_name": "Add Purchase Limit Middleware + Daily Cap Endpoint with Custom Validation",
  "skill_category": "ASP.NET Core Logic",
  "scenario": {
    "story": "A corporate purchasing portal exposes an API to place internal supply requests. To prevent budget overruns, the company enforces a daily purchase cap per department. Clients must send the department id and today’s requested amount. The API should reject requests that exceed the daily cap, and it must return a clear error response that includes the cap and the attempted amount. Operations also wants the cap check to be implemented as middleware so it can be applied consistently before hitting controllers.",
    "requirement": "Implement ONE feature: a department daily-cap check for purchase requests. Add custom middleware that reads department id from the request (header or route), looks up a cap using an injected service, and blocks the request with an HTTP error response when the new request would exceed the cap. Provide a controller endpoint that accepts a purchase request payload, uses custom model validation for cross-field rules, and returns appropriate IActionResult responses."
  },
  "targeted_objectives": [11, 13, 7],
  "additional_skills_required": [
    {
      "skill_name": "C# Basics",
      "used_learning_goal": 7,
      "justification": "Cap enforcement requires clear conditional branching to compute remaining budget and decide whether to block or allow the request."
    }
  ],
  "instructions": [
    "Create a request DTO representing a purchase attempt with fields such as departmentId, requestedAmount, and day (or rely on server date). Add data annotations for required fields and numeric ranges.",
    "Implement custom model validation (e.g., IValidatableObject) for cross-field rules such as: departmentId must be positive, requestedAmount must be greater than zero, and (if provided) the day must not be in the future.",
    "Create a small service abstraction that returns the daily cap for a department and the amount already spent today (these can be hard-coded/in-memory for the exercise). Register it with DI.",
    "Implement middleware that runs before the controller. It must read departmentId from the incoming request, call the cap service, and decide whether the request should proceed.",
    "If the request exceeds the remaining cap, short-circuit the pipeline: set an appropriate status code (e.g., 429 or 422), and write a JSON response containing departmentId, cap, alreadySpent, requestedAmount, and remaining.",
    "Create an attribute-routed controller action (POST) that binds the request body to the DTO. If ModelState is invalid, return BadRequest with validation details. If middleware allows the request, return Ok with a small payload confirming acceptance and the computed remaining budget.",
    "Ensure middleware uses HttpContext to set status code and response body and does not break model binding for the controller (avoid consuming the request body).",
    "Add minimal logging in the middleware and/or controller that includes departmentId and decision (allowed/blocked)."
  ],
  "validation_criteria": [
    {
      "criterion": "A custom middleware class exists and is added to the HTTP pipeline so it executes before the purchase controller action.",
      "related_learning_objective": 11
    },
    {
      "criterion": "The middleware reads departmentId from HttpContext.Request (header, query, or route) and uses it to perform the cap check.",
      "related_learning_objective": 13
    },
    {
      "criterion": "When the request model is invalid due to data annotations or custom validation, the controller action returns HTTP 400 (BadRequest) with validation details.",
      "related_learning_objective": 7
    },
    {
      "criterion": "When the requestedAmount exceeds the remaining daily cap, the middleware short-circuits the pipeline and returns a non-2xx status code with a JSON payload containing cap and requestedAmount.",
      "related_learning_objective": 0
    },
    {
      "criterion": "When the request is within the cap, the middleware allows the pipeline to continue and the controller returns HTTP 200 (OK).",
      "related_learning_objective": 0
    },
    {
      "criterion": "The JSON error payload produced by the middleware includes departmentId, cap, alreadySpent, requestedAmount, and remaining fields.",
      "related_learning_objective": 0
    }
  ],
  "hints": [
    "Keep the feature small: one DTO, one middleware, one controller action, and one tiny service for cap values.",
    "Middleware is best for rejecting requests before controllers run—make sure it can return a JSON response on its own.",
    "Avoid reading the request body in middleware unless you enable buffering; prefer reading departmentId from route/header to keep it simple.",
    "Use custom model validation for rules that involve multiple fields, not just single-property checks."
  ]
}

